  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA119-kiḷavi">itu ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi ceṟippaṟivuṟīiyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante informs of confinement while [HE] is behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA119">
<l>            tiṉaiyuṇ kēḻa liriyap puṉavaṉ</l>
<l>            ciṟupoṟi māṭṭiya peruṅkal laṭāa</l>
<l>            roṇkēḻ vayappuli paṭūu nāṭa</l>
<l>            ṉārtara vantaṉa ṉāyiṉum paṭappai</l>
<l>            yiṉamucup peruṅkalai naṉmēya lārum </l>
<l>            paṉmalark kāṉyāṟ ṟumpark karuṅkalai</l>
<l>            kaṭumpāṭṭu varuṭaiyoṭu tāvaṉa vukaḷum</l>
<l>            peruvarai nīḻal varukuvaṉ kuḷaviyoṭu</l>
<l>            kūviḷan tatainta kaṇṇiyaṉ yāvatu</l>
<l>            muyaṅkal peṟukuva ṉallaṉ </l>
<l>            pulavi koḷīiyartaṉ malaiyiṉum peritē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The man from a land,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the strong tiger with bright lustre is caught</l>
<l rend="indent">in a trap<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṭāar</term> must be seen here as an <term xml:lang="ta">aḷapeṭai</term> of <term xml:lang="ta">aṭār</term>. The only parallel from the old corpus is PN 19.5f., where the context is similar: that of a tiger going into a trap, a construction involving a stone and a <term xml:lang="ta">poṟi</term> (cf. next note).</note> with a big stone attached to a small mechanism<note place="foot">Here T.V.G. explains <term xml:lang="ta">poṟi</term> as a kind of "machine", the thing in question being a kind of trap to catch the wild pig (cf. NA 98.3).</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">by the field owner, so that the boar that eats the millet retreats,</l>
<l rend="indent3">even if he came to get full satisfaction(?),<note place="foot">It is quite difficult to find a satisfactory connection between the first six lines and the rest of the poem. Do we have to accept two unrelated halves here?</note></l>
<l>he who comes into the shade of the big mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the goats [and their] relatives leaping</l>
<l rend="indent">with the mountain sheep frolic with the black male monkey<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">karuṅkalai / kaṭumpāṭṭu varuṭaiyoṭu tāvaṉa ukaḷum</term>: the kind and number of the animals in question, as well as their syntactical relation, is far from clear.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">beyond the many-flowered forest river,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the big male of the langurs in a group becomes full</l>
<l rend="indent">with good grazing in the garden,</l>
<l rend="indent3">he with a chaplet full of Bael plants with wild jasmine,</l>
<l>he will not obtain any embrace at all.</l>
<l>May he get vexation bigger than his mountain.</l>
        </lg>
